label.value: regulation of complement activation, classical pathway

value.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the classical pathway of complement activation.

label.value: regulation of complement activation, alternative pathway

value.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the alternative pathway of complement activation.
Repression of transcription at silent mating-type loci by alteration of the structure of chromatin.
The directed movement of the nucleus along microtubules within the cell, mediated by motor proteins.
Construction of a new spindle pole body.

The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form an ascospore wall. During sporulation in Ascomycota, each ascospore nucleus becomes surrounded by a specialized spore wall, formed by deposition of spore wall components in the lumenal space between the outer and inner leaflets of the prospore membrane. An example of this process is found in Saccharomyces cerevisiae.
Polarized accumulation of cytoskeletal proteins (including F-actin) and regulatory proteins in a cell. An example of this is the actin cap found in Saccharomyces cerevisiae.

An endocytic patch that consists of an actin-containing structure found at the plasma membrane in cells; formed of networks of branched actin filaments that lie just beneath the plasma membrane and assemble, move, and disassemble rapidly. An example of this is the actin cortical patch found in Saccharomyces cerevisiae.
The contractile fiber of smooth muscle cells.
Electron-dense region associated with a smooth muscle contractile fiber.
Catalysis of the reaction: 1D-myo-inositol 4,5-bisphosphate + H2O = 1D-myo-inositol 4-phosphate + phosphate.
The posttranscriptional addition of methyl groups to specific residues in a tRNA molecule.
Any process involved in the maturation of a precursor Small SubUnit (SSU) ribosomal RNA (rRNA) molecule into a mature SSU-rRNA molecule.
The formation of a stable duplex DNA that contains one strand from each of the two recombining DNA molecules.
Binding to hemoglobin, an oxygen carrying, conjugated protein containing four heme groups and globin.
The chemical reactions and pathways involving a bacteriochlorophyll, any of the chlorophylls of photosynthetic bacteria. They differ structurally from the chlorophylls of higher plants.

The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of a bacteriochlorophyll, any of the chlorophylls of photosynthetic bacteria. They differ structurally from the chlorophylls of higher plants.

The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of bacteriochlorophyll, any of the chlorophylls of photosynthetic bacteria. They differ structurally from the chlorophylls of higher plants.

A thin cytoplasmic bridge formed between daughter cells at the end of cytokinesis. The midbody forms where the contractile ring constricts, and may persist for some time before finally breaking to complete cytokinesis.
The elongation of a fatty acid chain by the sequential addition of two-carbon units.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of bone mineralization.
Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of bone mineralization.
Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of bone mineralization.
Enables the transfer of inorganic diphosphate across a membrane.
The directed movement of inorganic diphosphate into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.
Binding to ankyrin, a 200 kDa cytoskeletal protein that attaches other cytoskeletal proteins to integral membrane proteins.

Binding to spectrin, a protein that is the major constituent of the erythrocyte cytoskeletal network. It associates with band 4.1 (see band protein) and actin to form the cytoskeletal superstructure of the erythrocyte plasma membrane. It is composed of nonhomologous chains, alpha and beta, which aggregate side-to-side in an antiparallel fashion to form dimers, tetramers, and higher polymers.

The series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of a member of the BMP (bone morphogenetic protein) family to a receptor on the surface of a target cell, and ending with the regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the activity of any BMP receptor signaling pathway.

label.value: positive regulation of transforming growth factor beta receptor signaling pathway

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of TGF-beta receptor signaling pathway activity.

label.value: negative regulation of transforming growth factor beta receptor signaling pathway

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of any TGF-beta receptor signaling pathway.

label.value: positive regulation of BMP signaling pathway

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of BMP signaling pathway activity.

label.value: negative regulation of BMP signaling pathway

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the BMP signaling pathway.
Binding to a small nucleolar RNA.
Any process that modulates the rate, direction or extent of axon extension.
Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of axon outgrowth.

label.value: nuclear receptor-mediated steroid hormone signaling pathway

value.value: A nuclear receptor-mediated signaling pathway initiated by a steroid binding to an intracellular receptor of the nuclear receptor protein family, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.
Binding to a small nucleolar ribonucleoprotein particle.

A nuclear receptor-mediated signaling pathway initiated by an estrogen binding to an intracellular receptor of the nuclear receptor protein family, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

A nuclear receptor-mediated signaling pathway initiated by an androgen binding to an intracellular receptor of the nuclear receptor protein family, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.
The series of molecular signals initiated by a ligand binding to a receptor located within a cell.

label.value: granulocyte macrophage colony-stimulating factor receptor complex

value.value: The heterodimeric receptor for granulocyte macrophage colony-stimulating factor.
The action of a molecule that contributes to the structural integrity of chromatin.

A ribonucleoprotein complex that contains at least one RNA of the small nuclear RNA (snRNA) class and as well as its associated proteins. These are typically named after the snRNA(s) they contain, e.g. U1 snRNP, U4/U6 snRNP, or 7SK snRNP. Many, of these complexes become part of the spliceosome involved in splicing of nuclear mRNAs. Others are involved in regulation of transcription elongation or 3'-end processing of replication-dependent histone pre-mRNAs.
The codon binding activity of a tRNA that positions an activated amino acid, mediating its insertion at the correct point in the sequence of a nascent polypeptide chain during protein synthesis.

definition.value: Note that this term can be used in place of the obsolete term 'transfer RNA ; GO:0005563'.

value.value: Behavior in a fully developed and mature organism.

definition.value: See also the biological process term 'behavior ; GO:0007610'.

value.value: Feeding behavior in a larval (immature) organism.

definition.value: See also the biological process term 'feeding behavior ; GO:0007631'.

value.value: Behavior in a larval form of an organism, an immature organism that must undergo metamorphosis to assume adult characteristics.

definition.value: See also the biological process term 'behavior ; GO:0007610'.

value.value: The process, occurring in the embryo, by which the anatomical structures of the genitalia are generated and organized.
The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the male genitalia over time, from its formation to the mature structure.
